prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Band7_z0p2_0p4
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Band 7 continuum observations of IR-bright galaxies from 0.2 < z < 0.4

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Requested sensitivity: We estimate the observed 350 GHz flux density by fitting the available 100-500 micron spectral energy distributions to modified blackbodies. The faintest galaxy in our sample is expected to be 1 mJy, so we request a sensitivity of 0.2 mJy to achieve 5sigma detections.
Imaging requirements: We will observe the 50 sources in this Science Goal using mulitple single pointings. For these detection experiments, we would like to NOT resolve the dust emission from these sources. We thus request an angular resolution of 1.1" - the lowest resolution possible in Band 7. Some of our sources may be slightly larger (see Science Case), but we should be able to apply a uv-taper in imaging to reduce the resolution without significant loss in sensitivity.
Correlator setup: We use the default Band 7 single continuum setup in TDM mode, and will combine the full 7.5 GHz aggregate bandwidth to achieve our sensitivity goals.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: The steady decline in the cosmic star formation rate density at z < 1 hints at a fundamental change in the processes that regulate star formation at this epoch. Star formation rates, merger rates, and galactic structure all evolve dramatically over this half of cosmic history. It is not understood whether this evolution is primarily due to a decline in the gas supply in galaxies or lower efficiency at which they can convert the interstellar medium into stars. We propose to measure the mass of the interstellar medium in a representative, statistically signifiant sample of 200 galaxies from z = 0.1-1 through ALMA observations of their 850 micron dust continuum emission. Our goal is to study the interstellar medium in both main sequence and starburst galaxies in order to study which mode of star formation dominates as a function of redshift during this critical epoch.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:scientificCategoryString: Cosmology and the High Redshift Universe
